body:
How about keeping all (legacy and flat) configs in the `plugin.configs` but when resolving the string specifier `S`:
Check whether `plugin.configs.S` is a flat config.
If it is a flat config, use it.
Otherwise try resolving with a known prefix (e.g. `flat/`), so `plugin.configs.flat/S`.
If it is a flat config, use it and otherwise throw an error that `S` is not resolvable.

So for example given:
```json
{
	"configs": {
		"recommended": { "extends": [] },
		"flat/recommended": { "plugin": {}, "rules": {} }	
	}
}
```
It first checks `recommended`, sees it is not a flat config, then checks `flat-recommended` and finds a compatible config.
This is how some eslint plugins are already organized (e.g. `typescript-eslint` or `eslint-plugin-n`).

